    "correctIndex": 0,
    "explanation": "7y3975706x6 is divisible by 72, clearly it will also be divisible by 9 and 8. For a number to be divisible by 9, sum of its digits must be divisible by 9. 7+y+3+9+7+5+7+0+6+x+6 50+x+y must be divisible by 9\t⇒ So x+y = 4 or 13 \t..(as x and y can’t be greater than 9) For x+y = 4 (x,y) = (0,4), (1,3), (2,2), (3,1), (4,0) For x+y = 13 (x,y) = (4,9), (5,8), (6,7), (7,6), (8,5), (9,4) We will check for the smallest value of x which is 0 Last three digits of the number are 606 which is not divisible by 8. Now we will check for the second smallest value of x which is 1 Last three digits of the number are 616 which is divisible by 8. Clearly x=1 and y=3 are the desired values. = 3\t√3x y\t+ 2 ⇒ √3(1) (3)\t+ 2",
    "sectionName": "Quantitative Aptitude",
    "testId": "test-ssc-cgl-full-3279"
